ty in this community, acting as a primary cause of stress-related disorders and a significant factor influencing the immune system. It is categorized into catastrophic events, life events, long-term psychological stress, and sudden environmental changes, all of which can have profound effects on mental and physical health. The relationship between psychosocial stress and the immune system underscores its importance in this community. [Data: Entities (2394), Relationships (2773, 2772)]\n\n## Immune system's role in the community\n\nThe immune system is a critical entity in this community, serving as the body's primary defense mechanism against infections and diseases. It is influenced by psychosocial stress, which can lead to changes in immune factors such as IL-2, IL-6, and IgM. These changes can weaken the immune system's ability to protect the body, highlighting the complex interplay between stress and immune function. [Data: Entities (913), Relationships (2773, 2779, 2780, 2781)]\n\n## Impact of IL-2 on immune function\n\nIL-2 is an immune factor whose levels decrease during stress, affecting immune function. This decrease can compromise the immune system's ability to respond to infections and diseases, making IL-2 a significant entity in understanding the effects of stress on health. [Data: Entities (2397), Relationships (2779)]\n\n## Impact of IL-6 on immune function\n\nIL-6 is an immune factor whose levels increase during stress, affecting immune function. Elevated levels of IL-6 can lead to chronic inflammation and other health issues, making it a key factor in the community's dynamics. [Data: Entities (2398), Relationships (2780)]\n\n## Impact of IgM on immune function\n\nIgM is an immune factor whose levels increase during stress, affecting immune function. While IgM is crucial for the initial immune response, its dysregulation due to stress can have negative health implications. [Data: Entities (2399), Relationships (2781)]\n\n## Stress-related disorders and their causes\n\nStress-related disorders are a group of mental disorders primarily caused by psychosocial stress, leading to abnormal psychological reactions. These disorders are often short-lived and can resolve upon the removal of the stressor, but they highlight the significant impact of stress on mental health. [Data: Entities (2393), Relationships (2772)]", "# Cognitive Behavioral Therapy and Associated Entities\n\nThis community centers around Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), a widely recognized psychological treatment method. Key entities include A. Ellis, the creator of Rational Emotive Behavior Therapy (REBT), which influenced CBT, and Cormier, who developed cognitive restructuring therapy. The community also includes therapeutic techniques like cognitive restructuring, cognitive demonstration, and reality testing, as well as pharmacological treatments such as Estazolam, Diazepam, and Alprazolam. These entities are interconnected through their roles in mental health treatment, with CBT serving as a foundational approach that integrates various techniques and treatments.\n\n## Cognitive Behavioral Therapy as the central entity\n\nCognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) is the cornerstone of this community, serving as a widely recognized and effective psychological treatment method. CBT is rooted in behavioral learning theory and cognitive psychology, focusing on modifying dysfunctional cognitions, emotions, and behaviors. Its structured, goal-oriented approach makes it versatile and practical for treating various mental health conditions, including depression, acute stress disorder, and eating disorders. CBT's integration with other therapeutic techniques and pharmacological treatments underscores its significance in the field of mental health [Data: Entities (640), Relationships (753, 2854, 851, 852, 853)].\n\n## A. Ellis's influence on CBT through REBT\n\nA. Ellis is a pivotal figure in this community, known for creating Rational Emotive Behavior Therapy 